          mean = df[col].mean()
          median = df[col].median()
          std_dev = df[col].std()
          min_val = df[col].min()
          max_val = df[col].max()
          skewness = df[col].skew()

          print(f"IQR (Interquartile Range): {iqr:.2f}")
          
          # Analyze the distribution based on the statistics
          if skewness > 1:
              skew_note = "The data is highly positively skewed."
          elif skewness < -1:
              skew_note = "The data is highly negatively skewed."
          elif 0.5 < skewness <= 1:
              skew_note = "The data is moderately positively skewed."
          elif -1 <= skewness < -0.5:
              skew_note = "The data is moderately negatively skewed."
          else:
              skew_note = "The data is approximately symmetric."
          
          print(f"Skewness Interpretation: {skew_note}")

          print(f"IQR indicates the spread of the middle 50% of the data. A higher IQR suggests more variability.")

      ​

      import pandas as pd
      import plotly.express as px
      ​
      # Step 1: Create a crosstab to get the frequency of specialization for each designation
      crosstab_data = pd.crosstab(df['Designation'], df['Specialization'])
      ​
      # Step 2: Reset the index to get Job Title as a column
      crosstab_data.reset_index(inplace=True)
      ​
      # Step 3: Use Plotly Express to create a stacked bar plot
      fig = px.bar(crosstab_data, 
                   x='Designation', 
                   y=crosstab_data.columns[1:],  # This takes all columns except the first (Job Title)
                   title='Job Title vs Specialization (Stacked Bar Plot)',
                   labels={'value': 'Number of Candidates', 'Job Title': 'Job Title'},
                   text_auto=True)
      ​
      # Step 4: Update layout to make it more readable
      fig.update_layout(barmode='stack', xaxis_title='Job Title', yaxis_title='Number of Candidates')
      fig.update_traces(textposition='inside')
      ​
      # Step 5: Show the plot
      fig.show()
